The old method was a three step process that required Leapfrog in the middle of the workflow to desurvey drillhole traces using its spherical arc approximation alogrithm. This new DDC script now condenses the three step process into one. Hence the user will only have to run the script with the formatted input files mentioned above.

Get Rstudio: If you do not have Rstudio installed on your device locally, the other option is to access Rstudio via Citrix.

Running Rstudio on your local device will naturally be faster and provide less complications due to the instability of the network and VPN at Oak Dam/Arcoona Station. To obtain Rstudio on your local device you may do so from the BHP service website https://bhp.service-now.com/sp. Type Rstudio in the search bar > Rstudio IDE, and request (It is free anyways!)

Once you have opened R locally or virtually, and the csvs are in its correct directory, you will need to open the script itself and run it. The location for this R script is here: [M:/Geology/leeshanea/R] as DDC.R To run the script click anywhere within the Source pane (default top left pane out of the 4 on your screen), Ctrl + A to select all, then Ctrl + Shift + S to run

Understanding the results

This table is the summary for each hole and their remaining distance to target. remain_dist shows how many meters left before the hole is about to intersect its target, hence if it is 0, it has passed its target and the column proj_dis_to_targ indicates the actual distance from the target. Otherwise it is the projected distance to target.

You may notice that the ProjectedvsPlan graphs plots weirdly at times. This artifact is only visual when the y-axis scale is small enough (0 - 5). This occurs due to the lack of alignment between the linear intperolations (lerp) of the projected data and the planned data. For example, if the lerped projected survey has points md = 444, 445 and 446, whilst the lerped planned survey only has 444 and 446, the distance between 444 and 446 points of both surveys could be etc. 0.1m, the point at 445 will be etc. 1m, hence a small spike in certain areas of the graph.

#### Install and load packages ####
packages <- c("readxl","lubridate","tidyverse","ggplot2", "plotly", "tictoc", "knitr", "janitor", "gridExtra", "grid")
package.check <- lapply(
  packages,
  FUN = function(x) {
    if (!require(x, character.only = TRUE)) {
      install.packages(x, dependencies = TRUE)
      library(x, character.only = TRUE)
    }
  }
)

#### Clear environment & Timer ####
rm(list = ls()) ## Clear global environment
tic ()

#### Functions ####
# Radians to degree function
rad <- function(r){
  r * pi / 180
}
#### Source and wd (Import data - Acquire & Geo input csvs) ####
# Pull survey and collar data from M drive
setwd ("M:/Final/ACQUIRE/Exports/LFM")
OKD_surv <- read.csv("OAKDAM_MGA94-53_sur.csv")
OKD_col <- read.csv("OAKDAM_MGA94-53_col.csv")

# Change directory to read inputs
setwd ("M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/DDC")
# Geo input csvs
Pjt_surv <- read.csv("Projection survey.csv")
plan_csv <- read.csv("Planned Survey.csv")
targ_csv <- read.csv("Targets.csv") # Change to all targets that team uses for LF?

# Initialize and clean dataframes
OKD_surv <- clean_names(OKD_surv)
OKD_col <- clean_names(OKD_col)
Pjt_surv <- clean_names(Pjt_surv)
plan_csv <- clean_names(plan_csv)
colnames(plan_csv)[1] <- "bhid"
targ_csv <- clean_names(targ_csv)
colnames(targ_csv)[5] <- "bhid"
Pjt_col <- OKD_col

#### QAQC check source ####
temp_check1 <- Pjt_surv %>% # Pjt surv
  arrange(desc(md)) %>%
  distinct(bhid, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(bhid, md)
temp_check2 <- targ_csv %>% # Target points
  select(bhid, pad_id, target_id)
temp_check3 <- plan_csv %>% # Plan surv
  arrange(desc(md)) %>%
  distinct(bhid, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(bhid, md)

check1 <- left_join(temp_check1, temp_check3, by = "bhid") %>%
  rename(proj_maxmd = md.x) %>%
  rename(plan_maxmd = md.y)
check2 <- check1 %>%
  filter(is.na(plan_maxmd)) %>%
  select(bhid)
if(nrow(check2) != 0){
  print("Missing in Planned Survey.csv") # Bhids in pjt but not in planned csv
  stop(paste0("bhid - ",check2$bhid," "))
}
check3 <- left_join(temp_check1, temp_check2, by = "bhid") %>%
  filter(is.na(target_id)) %>%
  select(bhid)
if(nrow(check3) != 0){
  print("No targets for") # Bhids in pjt but not in target csv
  stop(paste0("bhid - ",check3$bhid," "))
}
check4 <- left_join(check1, temp_check2, by = "bhid") 
print("QAQC on source csvs completed, processing these holes...") # QAQC message checkpoint
print(check4)

#### 1. Produce projection holes - Joining contractors projection to actual surveys in db ####
## Filter 
# Obtain latest md from OKD_surv
Pjt_merge_depth <- OKD_surv %>%
  arrange(desc(depth)) %>%
  distinct(bhid, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(bhid, depth)
# Merge OKD_surv with Pjtn surv to remove oudated Pjt'ed surv
surv_join1 <- left_join(Pjt_surv, Pjt_merge_depth, by = "bhid")
surv_join2 <- surv_join1 %>% # If Pjtn surv md(i) < OKD suv (i + nth), omit data row
  select(bhid, md, dip, gn_azi, depth) %>%
  mutate(filtering = md - depth) %>%
  filter(filtering > 0) %>%
  select(bhid, md, dip, gn_azi)
surv_append <- OKD_surv %>%
  select(bhid, depth, azimuth, dip)
# Rename
colnames(surv_append)[2] = "md"
colnames(surv_append)[3] = "gn_azi"

# Intialize Pjt_col EOH depth to max md from Pjt_surv
col_join1 <- surv_join2 %>% # Max md of projected survey
  arrange(desc(md)) %>%
  distinct(bhid, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(bhid, md)
Pjt_col_final <- left_join(Pjt_col, col_join1, by = "bhid") %>%
  mutate(eoh = coalesce(md,eoh)) %>% # Replace eoh with md, if md na, keep eoh
  select(-md)

# Final projection survey and collar, bind OKD_surv and Pjt_surv
Pjt_surv_final <- bind_rows(surv_join2, surv_append) %>%
  group_by(bhid) %>% # Grouping variable for .by_group
  arrange(md, .by_group = TRUE) #sort with bhid grouping

# Filter Pjt_surv_final for only current drilling - Pjt surv distinct
current_drillholes <- distinct(Pjt_surv, bhid) %>%
  mutate(temp = 1)
Pjt_col_final <- left_join(Pjt_col_final, current_drillholes, by = "bhid") %>%
  filter(temp == 1) %>%
  select(-temp)
Pjt_surv_final <- left_join(Pjt_surv_final, current_drillholes, by = "bhid") %>%
  filter(temp == 1) %>%
  select(-temp)

# Export out Pjt col and surv csvs
setwd ("M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/exports/DDC")
write.csv(Pjt_col_final, "Projection collar.csv", row.names = FALSE)
write.csv(Pjt_surv_final, "Projection survey.csv", row.names = FALSE)
print("Projection collar and survey csvs exported to M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/exports/DDC")

#### 2. Desurveying and Interpolation of projection holes ####
# Subset
temp1 <- Pjt_col_final %>%
  distinct(bhid)

desurv_lerp <- data.frame() # Int LERP df

print("2. Desurveying and interpolation of projection traces for...")
print(temp1) # List of traces to process

for (k in 1:nrow(temp1)){
  temp_col1 <- Pjt_col_final %>% 
    filter(bhid == temp1[k,]) %>%
    select(bhid, east, north, rl)
  temp_surv1 <- Pjt_surv_final %>%
    filter(bhid == temp1[k,])
  
  temp_colsurv <- left_join(temp_surv1, temp_col1, by = "bhid")
  temp_colsurv1 <- temp_colsurv %>%
    mutate(inclination = dip + 90) %>%
    mutate(length = md - lag(md, default = md[1])) # Length [i + 1] - [i]
  
  temp_colsurv2 <- temp_colsurv1 %>%
    mutate(northing = case_when(md == 0 ~ north, TRUE ~ 0))
  
  desurv <- temp_colsurv2 %>%
    mutate(northing = (length/2) * (sin(rad(lag(inclination, default = inclination[1]))) # North
                                    * cos(rad(lag(gn_azi, default = gn_azi[1]))) # Lag to take previous row
                                    + sin(rad(inclination))
                                    * cos(rad(gn_azi)))) %>%
    mutate(northing = cumsum(northing) + north) %>% # Decimals still stored
    mutate(easting = (length/2) * (sin(rad(lag(inclination, default = inclination[1]))) # East
                                   * sin(rad(lag(gn_azi, default = gn_azi[1]))) # Lag to take previous row
                                   + sin(rad(inclination))
                                   * sin(rad(gn_azi)))) %>%
    mutate(easting = cumsum(easting) + east) %>% # Decimals still stored
    mutate(rls = (length/2) * (cos(rad(lag(inclination, default = inclination[1])))
                               + cos(rad(inclination)))) %>%
    mutate(rls = rl - cumsum(rls)) # RL
  
  
  desurv_inverse_filter <- desurv %>% # data filtered out in next few lines kept here
    filter(length >= 1) %>% 
    filter(length < 2) %>% # Keeping desurveyed data that have length = 1 between md points to rbind into final at end
    select(bhid, md, easting, northing, rls)
  
  desurv <- desurv %>%
    filter(case_when(md == 0 ~ length == 0, # When md == 0, filter (take) length == 0
                     TRUE ~ length >= 2 )) # Everything else, filter length >= 2
  # Interpolation
  for (i in 1:nrow(desurv)){
    
    lerp_seq <- as.numeric((desurv[i + 1,9])) # md length
    
    if (is.na(lerp_seq)){ # When i + 1 in length is = 1 skip iteration. to value > from error in seq
      next
    } else if (lerp_seq == 1){ # When i + 1 goes beyond dataframe, skip iteration. NA error in seq
      next
    }
    
    east_dif <- desurv[i, 11] - desurv[i + 1, 11]
    north_dif <- desurv[i, 10] - desurv[i + 1, 10]
    rls_dif <- desurv[i, 12] - desurv[i + 1, 12]
    
    temp_desurv_lerp <- cbind(desurv[i, 1], desurv[i, 2], desurv[i, 11], desurv[i, 10], desurv[i, 12]) # Rbind current i iteration data
    desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, temp_desurv_lerp)
    
    print(paste0("2. Processing > ", temp1[k,], " @ " ,round(i/nrow(desurv), digits = 2) * 100, "%")) # Progress bar
    
    lerp_seq <- seq(1/lerp_seq, 0.999, 2/lerp_seq) # Lin interp even nodes from md length (2/lerp, change x = 2 for lerp resolution)
    
    for (j in 1:length(lerp_seq)){
      j <- lerp_seq[j]
      
      east_dif2 <- desurv[i, 11] - (east_dif * j)
      north_dif2 <- desurv[i, 10] - (north_dif * j)
      rls_dif2 <- desurv[i, 12] - (rls_dif * j)
      temp_md <- desurv[i, 2] + (desurv[i + 1, 9] * j)
      
      all_dif <- cbind(desurv[i,1], temp_md, east_dif2, north_dif2, rls_dif2) # Create single row data cbind
      all_dif <- na.omit(all_dif) # Get rid of na
      desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, all_dif) # Rbind everything within i to i + 1 sequence of iteration
    }
  }
  desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, desurv_inverse_filter) # rbind length = 1 data into interpolated data where length >=2 
}
Pjt_desurv <- desurv_lerp

                                    * cos(rad(lag(gn_azi, default = gn_azi[1]))) # Lag to take previous row
                                    + sin(rad(inclination))
                                    * cos(rad(gn_azi)))) %>%
    mutate(northing = cumsum(northing) + north) %>% # Decimals still stored
    mutate(easting = (length/2) * (sin(rad(lag(inclination, default = inclination[1]))) # East

                                   + sin(rad(inclination))

  desurv_inverse_filter <- desurv %>% # data filtered out in next few lines kept here
    filter(length >= 1) %>%

    select(bhid, md, easting, northing, rls)
  
  desurv <- desurv %>%
    filter(case_when(md == 0 ~ length == 0, # When md == 0, filter (take) length == 0
                     TRUE ~ length >= 2 )) # Everything else, filter length >= 2
  
  # Interpolation
  for (i in 1:nrow(desurv)){
    
    lerp_seq <- as.numeric((desurv[i + 1,9])) # md length

    } else if (lerp_seq == 1){ # When i + 1 goes beyond dataframe, skip iteration. NA error in seq

    }
    
    east_dif <- desurv[i, 11] - desurv[i + 1, 11]
    north_dif <- desurv[i, 10] - desurv[i + 1, 10]
    rls_dif <- desurv[i, 12] - desurv[i + 1, 12]
    
    temp_desurv_lerp <- cbind(desurv[i, 1], desurv[i, 2], desurv[i, 11], desurv[i, 10], desurv[i, 12]) # Rbind current i iteration data
    desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, temp_desurv_lerp)
    
    print(paste0("3. Processing > ", temp1[k,], " @ " ,round(i/nrow(desurv), digits = 2) * 100, "%")) # Progress bar
    
    lerp_seq <- seq(1/lerp_seq, 0.999, 2/lerp_seq) # Lin interp even nodes from md length (2/lerp, change x = 2 for lerp resolution)
    
    for (j in 1:length(lerp_seq)){
      j <- lerp_seq[j]
      
      east_dif2 <- desurv[i, 11] - (east_dif * j)
      north_dif2 <- desurv[i, 10] - (north_dif * j)
      rls_dif2 <- desurv[i, 12] - (rls_dif * j)

      desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, all_dif) # Rbind everything within i to i + 1 sequence of iteration
    }
  }
  desurv_lerp <- rbind(desurv_lerp, desurv_inverse_filter) # rbind length = 1 data into interpolated data where length >=2 
}
planned_desurv <- desurv_lerp

#### 4. Generate final dataframes for use, error codes needed? - CHECKPOINT ####
# Create act_desurv by filtering Pjt_desurv to OKD_col EOH
temp_col1 <- Pjt_desurv %>%
  distinct(bhid)
act_col <- left_join(temp_col1, OKD_col, by = "bhid") # Filter for bhid in pjt_desurv
act_col <- act_col %>% # Select EOH only

act_desurv <- left_join(Pjt_desurv, act_col, by = "bhid")
act_desurv <- act_desurv %>% # Uses interpolation in 2, which is built from act and proj surveys
  mutate(filter = eoh - md) %>% # Then filter out the proj based on EOH value in OKD_col
  filter(filter >= 0) %>%

bhid_subset <- Pjt_desurv %>%
  distinct(bhid)

# md seems to be jumbled up after desurv and lerp
Pjt_desurv <- Pjt_desurv %>%

  group_by(bhid) %>%

#### 5. Distance from actual to target ####
distance_remaining <- left_join(act_desurv,targ_csv, by = "bhid") %>% # Distance remaining to target from actual drilling
  mutate(distance = sqrt( # Pythagoras 
    (easting - x)^2 +
      (northing - y)^2 +
      (rls - z)^2)) %>%
  group_by(target_id) %>%
  summarise(distancetotarget = min(distance, na.rm = TRUE))
distance_remaining <- left_join(distance_remaining, targ_csv, by = "target_id") %>% # Add more details onto the table
  select(bhid, pad_id, distancetotarget, target_id, rig_id)
distance_remaining$distancetotarget <- round(distance_remaining$distancetotarget, digits = 1) # Rounding

#### 6. min distance to targets, table, Int pdf file for both 5 and 6 ####
target_deviation <- left_join(Pjt_desurv,targ_csv, by = "bhid") %>% # Distance remaining to target from actual drilling
  mutate(distance = sqrt( # Pythagoras 
    (easting - x)^2 +
      (northing - y)^2 +
      (rls - z)^2)) %>%
  group_by(target_id) %>%
  summarise(distancetotarget = min(distance, na.rm = TRUE))
target_deviation <- left_join(target_deviation, targ_csv, by = "target_id") %>% # Add more details onto the table
  select(bhid, pad_id, distancetotarget, target_id)
target_deviation$distancetotarget <- round(target_deviation$distancetotarget, digits = 1) # Rounding

distancereport <- left_join(target_deviation, distance_remaining, by = "target_id") %>%
  select(bhid.x, pad_id.x, distancetotarget.x, target_id, distancetotarget.y, rig_id) %>%
  rename(bhid = bhid.x) %>%
  rename(pad_id = pad_id.x) %>%
  rename(proj_dis_to_targ = distancetotarget.x) %>%
  mutate(remain_dist = distancetotarget.y - proj_dis_to_targ) %>%
  select(-distancetotarget.y) %>%
  relocate(remain_dist, .before = proj_dis_to_targ)

# Initialize pdf file
pdf(file = "M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/exports/DDC/DistanceReport.pdf")
grid.table(distancereport)

#### 7. actual + projected vs plan, graphing, min distance algorithm, Int pdf file ####
# Filter for max depth in either Pjt and planned
temp1 <- Pjt_desurv %>%
  group_by(bhid) %>%
  summarise(maxdepth = max(md, na.rm = TRUE))
temp2 <- planned_desurv %>%
  group_by(bhid) %>%
  summarise(maxdepth = max(md, na.rm = TRUE))
temp_maxdepth <- left_join(temp1, temp2, by = "bhid") %>%
  mutate(maxmd = pmin(maxdepth.x, maxdepth.y)) %>% # pmin performs parallel min function across individual elements, min performs across all
  select(bhid, maxmd)
temp_pjtmd <- left_join(Pjt_desurv, temp_maxdepth, by = "bhid") %>%
  mutate(temp_filter = maxmd - md) %>%
  filter(temp_filter >= 0) %>% # Filter out any data beyond max md
  select(-temp_filter)
temp_plannedmd <- left_join(planned_desurv, temp_maxdepth, by = "bhid") %>%
  mutate(temp_filter = maxmd - md) %>%
  filter(temp_filter >= 0) %>% # Filter out any data beyond max md
  select(-temp_filter)

# Vectorized version of minimum distance algorithm
min_distance_target <- left_join(temp_pjtmd, temp_plannedmd, by = c("bhid"), relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  rename(easting_pjt = easting.x) %>% 
  rename(northing_pjt = northing.x) %>%
  rename(rls_pjt = rls.x) %>%
  rename(easting_plan = easting.y) %>%
  rename(northing_plan = northing.y) %>%
  rename(rls_plan = rls.y) %>%
  na.omit(easting_plan) %>% # QAQC in case of any NAs (Could be removed)
  mutate(distance = sqrt( # Pythagoras 
    (easting_pjt - easting_plan)^2 +
      (northing_pjt - northing_plan)^2 +
      (rls_pjt - rls_plan)^2)) %>%
  group_by(bhid, md.x) %>% # Group by bhid and measured distance
  summarise(distancetotarget = min(distance, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  rename(md = md.x) %>%
  rename(distance = distancetotarget)

temp_subset <- min_distance_target %>%
  distinct(bhid, .keep_all = FALSE)

# Intialize pdf file
pdf(file = "M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/exports/DDC/ProjectedvsPlanReport.pdf")

This is 1 part of a 2 part process that is used to obtain the plots and deviation values from targets. This QRG will run you through the steps and required documents to run the scripts and the expected produced results. A troubleshoot section is attached at the end of the document.

If you do not have Rstudio installed on your device locally, the other option is to access Rstudio via Citrix. Running Rstudio on your local device will naturally be faster and provide less complications due to the instability of the network and VPN at Oak Dam/Arcoona Station. The code chunk below shows the input data that will be used throughout the script, firstly it draws data from the collar and survey file updated daily within the M drive.

Other inputs that it requires from the user (Geos) are the Projection Survey.csv and the Planned Survey.csv. Templates for how the content of the csv is formatted can be found a folder deeper within the Templates folder.

Note: Ensure that the BHID in the Planned survey matches to the BHID in the projection survey. This is mentioned specifically for redrills where AD47 may have been planned with that BHID, but is currently drilling as AD47X1. Hence the BHIDs in the planned survey must be of the same format.

Note: Contractor surveys are inconsistent with their formatting. Ensure that the data within the Projection Survey.csv has -dip and Grid Azimuth. The projection survey does not require you to knit your data with the live surveys. As it will be performed within the script itself

Your outputs will be a collection of graphs exported in a PDF format for you to snip and use in your reports. One of the PDFs is a distance report that shows the distance of the actual-projected trace from the target. The user (Geos) will have to look at the current drill depth of the hole to understand if the distance value is from the actual or the projected.

Below are examples of the graphs

The graph plotted above shows the distance between the projected and the planned traces. The projected trace is a combination of live (actual) and projection. The live data supersedes the projection data, hence an understanding of where the hole is currently progressing in MD (Measured drilling meters) is crucial. Generic ideas can be made from trends where inflection points are attempts at re-correcting drilling/navi drilling and global minimas are attempts at closing in on the target

The graph plotted above shows the section views and planned views with a 1:1 scale on both axis, hence the plan view will be exaggerated based on the direction of drilling. Red is the live (actual) survey, whilst light grey is the planned.

The final PDF which consists of only a table is for the user (Geos) to identify how close we are to hitting our targets. The value of the distance to target is based on the projection trace (which consists of live/actual and projection surveys). Hence, if the daily report mentions the current hole is past target, the distance is “actual distance from target”. Otherwise it is “projected distance from target”

Appendix

FAQ (Old method)

  1. I have populated the Projection survey.csv for the 1st part of the script but the output Projection survey.csv and Projection collar.csv does not show the holes I have populated in the input csv. Now when I upload my projections into Leapfrog it does not show up!
    • It is good practice to ensure the Planned Survey.csv has been populated correctly with the correct BHIDs. Another factor would be that the collar does not exist in the database yet (Collar not yet entered?), and that the LFM csvs in the M drive only updates daily mid-day (which is what this script references from).
  2. I have ran the script (Ctrl + A -> Ctrl + Shift + S) but nothing is happening? How do I know that my Rstudio has not frozen up/failed/finished etc.
    • After running the script, the console (bottom left panel) will show lines of code being ran, hence you would see movement as it goes through each line. However, there are some lines that are more complex. When this happens, a small stop sign at the top right of the console panel will appear, which would allow the user to interrupt the process. These are signs that the script is running. There are also expected run times mentioned below the header of each section.
  3. I have ran both scripts and the minimum distance output for one/some of the holes in the DistanceReport.pdf show Inf instead of expected values.
    • Data duplicates and format are the main culprits for this error. Ensure that the BHIDs are matched up correctly across all input csvs (sometimes there might be a space behind typed BHID etc. ~AD52 ~). Data duplicates such as duplicate surveys would prevent Leapfrog from de-surveying that respective hole’s trace, and hence would not be exported as a Actual/PlannedCoordinates.csv to be used in the 2nd script. These can be troubleshooted from Leapfrog itself to identify where the duplicate is, which can be fixed through Leapfrog itself (ignore row) or managed in the Projection survey.csv and Planned survey.csv (recommended method for handover to multiple users of the script).
  4. The SectionViewReport.pdf has missing holes. However, they have been generated fine in the ProjectedvsPlanReport.pdf and DistanceReport.pdf
    • The plan and section graphs in the report are plotted based on the data generated from AcQuire (LFM). If the surveys from the contractors are still not uploaded into the database, or the core depth in AcQuire is = 0, nothing will be plotted. Take note if this has been rectified straight away in the database, the data will only be available mid-day as that is when the database dumps the csvs into the M drive daily.

#### Subset for min distance trace and graphing ####
fil1 <- MinDis_csv %>% # Create list of hole ids to subset
  distinct(BHID)

for (k in 1:nrow(fil1)){
  
  pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0,      # Minimum value of the progress bar
                       max = nrow(fil1), # Maximum value of the progress bar
                       style = 3,    # Progress bar style (also available style = 1 and style = 2)
                       width = 50,   # Progress bar width. Defaults to getOption("width")
                       char = "=")   # Character used to create the bar
  
  fil2 <- MinDis_csv %>%
    filter(BHID == fil1[k,])
  
  # Initialize DF
  df1 <- data.frame() # For 2nd for loop distance results for each iteration
  min_dist <- data.frame() # min() applied onto df1
  
  # Loop through source DF, and run min distance function
  for (i in 1:nrow(fil2)){
    print(paste0(i,"/",nrow(fil2))) # Progress bar
    
    for (j in 1:nrow(fil2)){
      dist <- sqrt(((fil2[j,3] - fil2[i,6])^2) +
                     ((fil2[j,4] - fil2[i,7])^2) +
                     ((fil2[j,5] - fil2[i,8])^2))
      df1 <- rbind(df1, dist)
    }
    output <- c(fil2[i,2], min(df1)) # Numeric output
    min_dist <- rbind(min_dist, output) # Append into empty DF
    df1 <- data.frame() # Clean df1 for inner "for" loop again
  }
  # Format col names
  colnames(min_dist)[1] <- "MD"
  colnames(min_dist)[2] <- "Distance"
  
  # Merge back with source, formatting for plotting
  fil2 <- fil2 %>%
    mutate(Distance = min_dist$Distance)
  colnames(fil2)[1] <- "BHID"
  
  # Graph plotting, categorize colour based on BHID uniques
  plot <- fil2 %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = MD, y = Distance, colour = BHID)) + 
    geom_line() +
    labs(title = "Projected vs Plan")
  
  # Save plot in directory as "Plot.png"
  # nam <- fil1[k,] # Get name
  # ggsave(gsub(" ", "", paste(nam,".png")))
  print(plot)
  setTxtProgressBar(pb, k)
  close(pb)
}
dev.off()

#### Subset for min distance targets ####
# Format
colnames(MinDis_csv)[3] <- "Actual_X"
colnames(MinDis_csv)[4] <- "Actual_Y"
colnames(MinDis_csv)[5] <- "Actual_Z"
colnames(MinDis_csv)[6] <- "Planned_X"
colnames(MinDis_csv)[7] <- "Planned_Y"
colnames(MinDis_csv)[8] <- "Planned_Z"
MinDis_csv <- MinDis_csv %>%
  select(-Planned_X, -Planned_Y, -Planned_Z)

# Filter csv$MD >1000? to minimize iteration time??? Hardcoding, assuming we never target <1000m MD. Similar concept below

merge_csv <- left_join(csv_targets, MinDis_csv, by = "BHID", relationship = "many-to-many") %>%
  select(-Pad_ID) %>%
  relocate(BHID, .before = x) %>%
  relocate(MD, .after = BHID) %>%
  relocate(TargetID, .after = Actual_Z)

fil1 <- merge_csv %>% # Create list of hole ids to subset
  distinct(TargetID)

# Initialize DF
df1 <- data.frame() # For 2nd for loop distance results for each iteration
min_dist <- data.frame() # min() applied onto df1

for (k in 1:nrow(fil1)){ # Filter to make iterations quicker, assumes XYZ target is within 100m of trace
  
  pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0,      # Minimum value of the progress bar
                       max = nrow(fil1), # Maximum value of the progress bar
                       style = 3,    # Progress bar style (also available style = 1 and style = 2)
                       width = 50,   # Progress bar width. Defaults to getOption("width")
                       char = "=")   # Character used to create the bar
  setTxtProgressBar(pb, k)
  
  MinDis_csv <- merge_csv %>%
    filter(TargetID == fil1[k,]) %>%
    filter(Actual_Z < z + 100, Actual_Z > z - 100) %>%
    filter(Actual_X < x + 100, Actual_X > x - 100) %>%
    filter(Actual_Y < y + 100, Actual_Y > y - 100)
  
  # Loop through source DF, and run min distance function
  for (i in 1:nrow(MinDis_csv)){
    for (j in 1:nrow(MinDis_csv)){
      dist <- sqrt(((MinDis_csv[j,3] - MinDis_csv[i,6])^2) +
                     ((MinDis_csv[j,4] - MinDis_csv[i,7])^2) +
                     ((MinDis_csv[j,5] - MinDis_csv[i,8])^2))
      df1 <- rbind(df1, dist)
    }
    output <- c(MinDis_csv[i,2], min(df1), fil1[k,]) # Numeric output
    min_dist <- rbind(min_dist, output) # Append into empty DF
    df1 <- data.frame() # Clean df1 for inner "for" loop again
  }
  close(pb)
}

# Obtain min for each unique target
colnames(min_dist)[1] <- "MD"
colnames(min_dist)[2] <- "Distance"
colnames(min_dist)[3] <- "TargetID"
min_dist <- min_dist %>%
  group_by(TargetID) %>%
  mutate(MinimumDistance = min(as.numeric(Distance), na.rm = T)) %>%
  arrange(TargetID) %>%
  distinct(TargetID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(TargetID, MinimumDistance)

fil1 <- merge_csv %>%
  distinct(TargetID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(TargetID, BHID)

min_dist <- left_join(min_dist, fil1, by = "TargetID") %>%
  na.omit(min_dist)

min_dist$MinimumDistance <- round(min_dist$MinimumDistance, digits = 1)

setwd ("M:/Geology/leeshanea/R/csv/database") # DB wd
DistanceReportDB <- read.csv("DistanceReportDB.csv")

min_dist_DB <- min_dist %>%
  mutate(AppendDate = as.character.Date(Sys.Date()))

DistanceReportDB <- rbind(DistanceReportDB, min_dist_DB)

write.csv(DistanceReportDB, "DistanceReportDB.csv",row.names = FALSE)
